Computer Language: (("Teaching Languages" "How to Design Programs" "Intermediate Student with lambda") (#(#t quasiquote repeating-decimal #f #t none) #f ()))
>Description:
A student of mine submitted code that appears to use Unicode character \u2212 (the minus sign) instead of a dash.  Racket then appears to report that, e.g., bst-key is not defined.  It is actually bst<\u2212>key that is not defined, but my student was not able to diagnose the problem, and neither were my TAs.

I don't know how this came about, but I am submitted a change request that DrRacket be made aware that 'minus sign', 'en dash', and maybe also 'em dash' are all common ways to write ASCII 45 incorrectly.  In DrRacket's default font, these characters are barely distinguishable, and there needs to be a way to give a better error message.
>How-To-Repeat:
1. 
(define-struct bst (left key value right))

2. (define (every-key? bst p?)
  (cond [(false? bst) true]
        [(bst? bst)
         (cond 
           [(p? (bst−key bst)) 
            (and (every-key? (bst-left bst) p?) 
                 (every-key? (bst-right bst) p?))]
           [(not (p? (bst−key bst))) false])]))

3. Run

4. Resulting message: bst−key: this function is not defined
>Fix:
>Audit-Trail:
From: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
To: "nr@cs.tufts.edu" <nr@cs.tufts.edu>,
        "bugs@racket-lang.org" <bugs@racket-lang.org>
Cc: "nobody@racket-lang.org" <nobody@racket-lang.org>,
        "bug-notification@racket-lang.org" <bug-notification@racket-lang.org>
Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/14197: Unicode confusion results in trouble for
 beginning students, TAs
Date: Sun, 24 Nov 2013 18:42:41 -0600

 --089e01494a1633c1d104ebf5a45f
 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
