 <div dir=3D"ltr">Just to comment on this. =C2=A0This has, on a first glance=
 , the hallmarks of a copy-and-paste from a web page. =C2=A0&quot;\u2212&quo=
 t; is a minus sign, but has one additional property: it&#39;s non-breaking =
 so that, for example, web pages won&#39;t treat it as regular hyphenation t=
 hat can be broken across lines. =C2=A0That is, you&#39;d observe these char=
 acters in typographic contexts, such as on the web.=C2=A0<div>
 
 <br></div><div>It would be rare for someone to try to intentionally type it=
  in a regular, programmer-friendly text editor. =C2=A0I&#39;d ask the stude=
 nt if they either were editing their original program in Microsoft Word or =
 some word processor or on some editor that isn&#39;t programmer-friendly.<d=
 iv>
 
 <div><br></div></div></div></div><div class=3D"gmail_extra"><br><br><div cl=
 ass=3D"gmail_quote">On Sun, Nov 24, 2013 at 4:40 PM,  <span dir=3D"ltr">&lt=
 ;<a href=3D"mailto:nr@cs.tufts.edu" target=3D"_blank">nr@cs.tufts.edu</a>&g=
