 <blockquote class=3D"gmail_quote" style=3D"margin:0 0 0 .8ex;border-left:1p=
 x #ccc solid;padding-left:1ex">A new problem report is waiting at<br>
 =C2=A0 <a href=3D"http://bugs.racket-lang.org/query/?cmd=3Dview&amp;pr=3D14=
 197" target=3D"_blank">http://bugs.racket-lang.org/query/?cmd=3Dview&amp;pr=
 =3D14197</a><br>
 <br>
 Reported by Norman Ramsey for release: 5.3.6<br>
 <br>
 *** Description:<br>
 A student of mine submitted code that appears to use Unicode character \u22=
 12 (the minus sign) instead of a dash. =C2=A0Racket then appears to report =
 that, e.g., bst-key is not defined. =C2=A0It is actually bst&lt;\u2212&gt;k=
 ey that is not defined, but my student was not able to diagnose the problem=
 , and neither were my TAs.<br>
 
 
 <br>
 I don&#39;t know how this came about, but I am submitted a change request t=
 hat DrRacket be made aware that &#39;minus sign&#39;, &#39;en dash&#39;, an=
 d maybe also &#39;em dash&#39; are all common ways to write ASCII 45 incorr=
 ectly. =C2=A0In DrRacket&#39;s default font, these characters are barely di=
 stinguishable, and there needs to be a way to give a better error message.<=
 br>
 
 
 <br>
 *** How to repeat:<br>
 1.<br>
 (define-struct bst (left key value right))<br>
 <br>
 2. (define (every-key? bst p?)<br>
 =C2=A0 (cond [(false? bst) true]<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 [(bst? bst)<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0(cond<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0[(p? (bst=E2=88=92key bst))<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 (and (every-key? (bst-left bst) p=
 ?)<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0(every-key? (=
 bst-right bst) p?))]<br>
 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0[(not (p? (bst=E2=88=92key bst))) =
 false])]))<br>
 <br>
 3. Run<br>
 <br>
 4. Resulting message: bst=E2=88=92key: this function is not defined<br>
 <br>
 *** Environment:<br>
 unix &quot;Linux homedog 3.2.0-4-686-pae #1 SMP Debian 3.2.51-1 i686 GNU/Li=
 nux&quot; (i386-linux/3m) (get-display-depth) =3D 32<br>
