 On Sun, Nov 24, 2013 at 9:51 PM, Danny Yoo <dyoo@hashcollision.org> wrote:
 
 > Just to comment on this.  This has, on a first glance, the hallmarks of a
 > copy-and-paste from a web page.  "\u2212" is a minus sign, but has one
 > additional property: it's non-breaking so that, for example, web pages
 > won't treat it as regular hyphenation that can be broken across lines.
 >  That is, you'd observe these characters in typographic contexts, such as
 > on the web.
 >
 > It would be rare for someone to try to intentionally type it in a regular=
 ,
 > programmer-friendly text editor.  I'd ask the student if they either were
 > editing their original program in Microsoft Word or some word processor o=
 r
 > on some editor that isn't programmer-friendly.
 >
 >
 >
